<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Letters to the Editor: Share options for the not so rich
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MALCOLM HURLSTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, May I correct the impression given in your column 'Labour names share
option 'millionaires' ' (August 19) that the discretionary options scheme
used for executives is different from that for other employees.
There is a single scheme under the 1984 Finance Act which covers all
employees, whether executives or not. In practice it has been used mainly
for executives and has become popularly known as a result as the 'executive
share option scheme'.
This however is a misnomer and there is a current trend (Wellcome, the
pharmaceuticals group, is an example) towards using the option scheme for
large numbers of employees.
Malcolm Hurlston,
The Esop Centre,
London WC1E 7AA
</TEXT>
<XX>
