<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It seems that those of us who choose our ice cream by taste are in a
minority. Haagen-Dazs is chosen because of its sexy advertising and Ben and
Jerry's because of its 'caring' image: eat a cornet and save a rain forest.
The last in the current series of The Business reports on the ice cream war
(7.30 BBC2). The BBC1 tabloid science series QED reports on another war: the
one between Bruce Silcock and his neighbours. Mr Silcock wants planning
permission to develop the world's biggest maggot farm in Essex (8.30). The
BBC2 series Under The Sun screens the first of three programmes on the lives
of Hamar women in Ethiopia. It seems they have a creation myth which is
rather more attractive than the Adam and Eve version: in the beginning two
people were created, one smiled and became a woman and the other kept his
mouth shut and became a man (9.30). BBC Proms 1994 is a recording of the
second half of last Saturday's Brahms' Night, with Carlo Maria Giulini
conducting (10.00). Can the One Day International produce cricket as
exciting as that in the third Test? (BBC1 11.00).
