<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Lang sets up advice panel on quangos
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, yesterday acted to stem criticism of the
growing use of quangos in the National Health Service by creating a
committee of leading public figures to advise him on appointments to health
boards and NHS trusts.
The new committee is chaired by Mr Norman Irons, the Scottish National party
member who is lord provost of Edinburgh. Mr Alex Salmond, leader of the SNP,
described Mr Lang's move as a humiliating climbdown forced by public concern
over 'the stuffing of health-service quangos by Tory placemen'.
The proliferation in Scotland of boards nominated by the Scottish secretary
has aroused criticism because their members are not elected. It is said that
they include disproportionate numbers of Conservatives in a country where
only a quarter of the electorate voted Tory in the 1992 general election.
Mr Lang said that he had sought a broader spread of political views among
people on quangos after the general election, asking leaders of opposition
parties to make nominations, inviting individuals to put themselves forward
and seeking nominations from more outside organisations.
The party leaders ignored the invitation but Mr Lang nominated people such
as Mr Campbell Christie, general secretary of the Scottish Trades Union
Congress, and Mrs Susan Baird, a former Labour lord provost of Glasgow, to
NHS trust boards.
Mr Lang said yesterday that 58 per cent of appointments made since the
general election had been from among people nominated by themselves or
outside bodies. About 40 per cent were women.
The other members of the new committee are: Mrs Jean McFadden, former Labour
leader of Glasgow District Council; the Rt Rev Mario Conti, Roman Catholic
bishop of Aberdeen; Mr Hugh Morison, director general of the Scotch Whisky
Association; and Dr Anthony Toft, president of the Royal College of
Physicians of Edinburgh.
Mr George Robertson, shadow Scottish secretary, said: 'Appointing yet
another quango to choose more quangos is no real answer in a democracy.' The
answer was to establish a Scottish parliament to which boards would be
accountable.
There is no English equivalent of the committee, although the Department of
Health is setting up a database of potential board members.
</TEXT>
