FT  25 AUG 94 / Rail union to ballot its Tube members
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The executive of the RMT transport union yesterday decided to ballot London
Underground workers on a series of one-day strikes over pay.
The move followed a similar decision by Aslef, the train drivers' union, on
Tuesday. The RMT's 8,000 members and Aslef's 2,000 drivers on London
Underground will vote next month on whether to support a series of one-day
stoppages in protest at an imposed 2 per cent pay rise.
If Underground workers vote to strike their action could be co-ordinated
with the stoppages by RMT rail signal staff working for Rail-track.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general-secretary, said: 'Despite promises made by
London Underground of a new dawn following the companycost-cutting programme
introduced three years ago, Underground workers are still waiting.'
The RMT announcement yesterday of a further 24-hour strike by Railtrack
signal workers on September 8 means the action will take place during the
annual Trades Union Congress, which is to be chaired by Mr Knapp.
