<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Exams under pressure to make the grade: John Authers on
fears that new vocational qualifications may do more harm than good
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Results for the first advanced-level General National Vocational
Qualifications (GNVQs) are announced today. But the qualification itself is
under even more rigorous scrutiny than the students.
This follows an attack by Professor Alan Smithers of Manchester University,
a government adviser on vocational education. He said: 'If GNVQs are not
significantly improved, far from revitalising our education system, they
will do harm.'
GNVQs do not involve conventional examinations as the GCE A-level does.
Instead, candidates must complete a series of units, passing each before
they earn the overall qualification.
The National Council for Vocational Qualifications, the agency which
oversees the qualifications, uses the driving test as an analogy.
But Prof Smithers said: 'The way GNVQs operate it is as if your driving
instructor were also your examiner and he or she ticked off whether you
could use the clutch and steering wheel separately but did not assess your
overall performance. Moreover, under the new funding arrangements, they
would only be paid if you passed.'
The attack by Prof Smithers and other conservative academics was damaging,
as the government wants GNVQs to be ranked equally with academic GCE
A-levels both for university entrance and for vocational training. Ministers
want 25 per cent of all 16-year-olds to enter for them by 1996.
Sir Ron Dearing, the government's chief curriculum adviser, intends to
extend the GNVQ structure to cover 14-to-16-year-olds from next year,
allowing them to take pre-vocational courses alongside existing academic
GCSEs.
Mr Tim Boswell, further and higher education minister, took action earlier
this year to address the criticisms of the qualifications. He said: 'We want
GNVQs to have parity of esteem with GCE A-levels. But we recognise that
esteem must be earned - it cannot be conferred by government, the CBI or
anyone else.'
Announcing a plan to tighten the qualification, he said it was necessary to:
Improve external testing.
Provide more training for external verifiers.
Clarify the grading criteria. Clarify what knowledge was needed for a GNVQ.
Provide clearer guidance for teachers on marking coursework, grading and
designing courses.
Tighten criteria for accrediting schools and colleges offering GNVQs.
Mr John Hillier, chief executive of the national council, said yesterday
that all of Mr Boswell's points would be implemented - either this year, for
external tests and grading, or next year.
He added that all elements of this year's pilot of GNVQs had been externally
assessed by awarding bodies, and by the government inspectorate Ofsted, the
further-education funding councils and the Department of Employment's
quality assurance division.
Mr Hillier admitted that this level of supervision could not be sustained
once GNVQs were taken more widely, but said that there were compulsory
external tests for all compulsory units.
He added that the apparent recognition of GNVQs by university admissions
tutors and increased interest from 16-year-olds gave grounds for
encouragement.
While 3,800 students entered for the initial pilot of advanced GNVQs in
1992, the results for which are announced today, about 37,000 registered
last year, and at least 50,000 are expected to register next month.
Ms Tina Townsend, chief executive of the Business and Technology Education
Council, one of the awarding bodies, pointed out that fewer than a third of
students who registered for advanced GNVQs two years ago had gained an
award.
She said: 'It shows the exams are tough and that you need a great deal of
determination and stamina to succeed.'
</TEXT>
