<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Swans takeover deal in jeopardy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The survival prospects of Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder in
receivership, dimmed yesterday as the Ministry of Defence disclosed that
there was a problem with a contract transfer deal.
The MoD said the disagreement on the price at which the company's sole
contract should be transferred to its only prospective purchaser was a
'major obstacle'.
The chances of a sale of Swans to French-based Soffia/ Constructions
Mecaniques de Normandie depend on a deal in which CMN would take on Swans'
frigate contract from the MoD and subcontract it to the receiver, Price
Waterhouse.
Price Waterhouse has said that unless CMN starts paying Swans' technical and
design team by next Wednesday they will be made redundant immediately. This
would effectively end the company's chances of bidding for future work and
being sold as a going concern.
Yesterday the MoD said CMN was unwilling to negotiate on the price for the
transfer of the contract for the three Type 23 frigates that Swans was
fitting out when it went into receivership in May last year. The
receivership followed its failure to win an MoD helicopter carrier order.
The MoD said: 'Price is the major obstacle and they are unwilling to
negotiate on price.' It added there was 'little benefit' to the MoD, the
defence budget or the taxpayer in CMN's 'very conditional' agreement, but it
remained ready to negotiate.
CMN also had to satisfy a number of requirements, the MoD said, including
financial and performance guarantees.
Last month the MoD and CMN agreed a price of Pounds 57.7m for the contract
for the three frigates. Since two have been completed and handed over,
between 10 per cent and 15 per cent of this sum, relating to the last
frigate due for completion in late October, would actually change hands.
Mr Fred Henderson, CMN's lead negotiator, said yesterday that the MoD wanted
to drop the price to Pounds 57m.
He said: 'We'd say the key obstacle is the MoD's unwillingness to go through
with the price it agreed on July 19.'
He has called for an urgent meeting with the MoD but said he was not very
hopeful about CMN's chances of buying Swans.
</TEXT>
