<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Loophole tightens around tax gurus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax advisers were yesterday trying to find new ways through the
ever-diminishing loophole which allows companies to avoid National Insurance
contributions by paying employees in kind.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, announced on Tuesday that
gemstones and fine wines would be treated as earnings and therefore be
liable for National Insurance contributions.
The measure extended moves by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, in the last
Budget to prevent gold bars and other tradeable commodities being used to
avoid contributions.
Mr Jim Yuill, director of social security services at accountant Ernst &amp;
Young, said: 'There are other ways of avoiding national insurance
contributions which have not yet been tried and we will be bringing them to
the fore in the next few weeks.'
He declined to be specific, in case of a pre-emptive move by the authorities
to block the proposals.
There are still a few NIC avoidance measures in existence, however. Mr Yuill
cited the controversial use of single-premium insurance policies. The DSS
says that there is legislation which should catch life insurance policies
but some accountants disagree. 'I'm sure it will end up in the courts,' Mr
Yuill said.
He added: 'The employer takes out a policy on the life of the employee for a
small amount, say Pounds 100, which is caught by NICs. The trick then is to
inflate the value of the policy by making a second and large payment which
escapes NIC liability. The employee then cashes the policy in.'
Other tricks to make payments in kind include giving high street store gift
vouchers, paying for employees' holidays and buying cars for them.
Like gold bars, diamonds and wine, these are taxable benefits but they have
not been widely favoured by employees because they are not as easily
encashable.
Mr Martin Kaye, managing-director of Stoy Benefit Consulting, said: 'It will
never be the same again.' He believed that one alternative for employers was
to turn to antiques, which have a mature market in the auction rooms.
</TEXT>
<XX>
