<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Bhutto denounces N-bomb claim: Opposition backtracks on
Sharif's assertion of nuclear capability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FARHAN BOKHARI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISLAMABAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Benazir Bhutto, Pakistan's prime minister, yesterday denounced as
irresponsible the assertion by former premier Nawaz Sharif that Pakistan has
nuclear weapons. Mr Sharif on Tuesday warned that any attack on Pakistan by
India could spark nuclear war between them.
India has seized the occasion to demand international action to halt any
nuclear weapons programme in Pakistan.
'The curtain of ambiguity about Pakistan's nuclear programme has fallen
off,' a Foreign Ministry spokesman in New Delhi said. 'It is a matter of
grave concern that Pakistan is actively pursuing this nuclear weapons
programme and is clandestinely procuring materials in this regard, as is
evident from recent reports,' he said.
The Indian spokesman was referring to investigations by Berlin authorities
into an alleged conspiracy to smuggle plutonium, used in the manufacture of
nuclear weapons, to Pakistan. Islamabad has denied involvement in any
plutonium plot.
Pakistan's opposition Moslem League party yesterday tried to back away from
Mr Sharif's statement that Pakistan had produced nuclear weapons.
Pakistan and India have fought two wars over Kashmir which both nations say
belongs to them. They came near a third war in 1990 and many fear any future
battle could quickly escalate into a nuclear exchange.
Like India, Pakistan is believed to have all the necessary components needed
for a bomb and the ability to assemble one in a matter of days or even
hours.
Pakistan's military and political leaders say the nuclear programme is
needed to deter India, its arch-rival. But successive governments, including
Mr Sharif's, have maintained that the country has stopped short of building
a bomb.
Mr Sharif refused to answer journalists' questions after a three-hour
meeting of his party's leadership in Islamabad yesterday. Instead, Mr
Chaudhary Shujaat Hussain, an opposition senator, accused Ms Bhutto's
government of 'exploiting the issue surrounding Mr Sharif's statement, to
divert attention from a planned opposition campaign next month'.
But some officials suspected Mr Sharif had sparked the controversy in an
effort to seek public support, especially from nationalists, ahead of an
anti-government protest planned to begin in about three weeks.
Others, however, suggested he had probably miscalculated the sensitivity of
the issue. 'Sharif must now be thinking it was wrong to make such a
statement in public. The nuclear issue can be extremely testy in the west,'
one senior western diplomat said last night.
</TEXT>
