<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Bonn coalition in tax dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's coalition partners are at loggerheads over tax policies as the
federal election campaign enters its final phase before voting on October
16. Mr Gunther Rexrodt, economics minister and a Free Democrat, wants the
budget deficit held steady, instead of being reduced further, to leave room
for tax cuts. The finance minister, Mr Theo Waigel, has dismissed the idea,
not only on behalf of his own Christian Social Union, but also in the name
of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats.
Mr Rexrodt made his proposal in a campaign debate on Monday night with Mr
Oskar Lafontaine, the opposition Social Democrat tipped to become finance
minister if the SPD wins in October. Seeking to counter the SPD's campaign
promise to implement a programme of swift and huge tax cuts for middle
wage-earners, Mr Rexrodt suggested the government keep the deficit high to
finance its own tax reductions. Attacking the idea, Mr Waigel insisted
yesterday that 'there will be no tax reductions without compensating
revenues.' Mr Rexrodt, however, in defending his proposal, cited progress in
consolidating the federal budget, adding that the government could finance
tax cuts by keeping the deficit at 2 per cent of gross domestic product in
1998 instead of cutting it to 0.5 per cent as planned. 'There would be room
for tax cuts totalling more than DM50bn (Pounds 21bn),' he said.
