<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / Archer says share order 'grave error': Labour calls for
second opinion on DTI report into Anglia deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Archer, the bestselling author and former Conservative Party deputy
chairman, last night said it was a 'grave error' to have placed the orders
to buy shares in Anglia Television, which have been the focus of a
Department of Trade and Industry investigation into alleged insider dealing.
In a statement, his solicitor Lord Mishcon, speaking on his behalf, said:
'It was a grave error when his wife was a director of Anglia to have allowed
his name to be associated with the purchase and sale of shares in that
company on behalf of a third party.'
The statement continued: 'His deepest regret is the embarrassment needlessly
caused to Lady Archer in this matter.'
Last week the Financial Times disclosed that Lord Archer's orders to buy
Anglia shares were the subject of the five-month DTI investigation. Since
then, he has refused to make any statements on the record about the affair
until last night.
Lady Archer said last night from her home that she was standing by her
husband: 'I'm still here and I'm staying here,' she said.
In response to a a question about whether she intended to resign from the
Anglia board, Lady Archer said: 'I'm still on the board.'
Anglia, now a subsidiary of MAI, said yesterday that its directors were
'happy to accept that she did not pass on inside information'.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, decided at the end of
July not to launch any prosecutions after the completion of the inquiry and
after receiving independent legal advice.
Robin Cook, Labour's trade spokesman, said last night that Lord Archer's
statement 'makes it all the more important that we get a second opinion on
the DTI report'.
Earlier this week, Mr Cook urged Mr Heseltine to pass the DTI report to the
Crown Prosecution Service, to ascertain whether the CPS concurred with the
DTI's decision to take no further action against Lord Archer.
Lord Archer said last night that the facts about the transactions which have
been disclosed in the press over the past week had been known to the DTI
inspectors.
In January, Lord Archer gave stockbrokers Charles Stanley detailed
instructions for the purchase of two parcels of Anglia Television shares
fewer than four working days before MAI announced a Pounds 292m takeover bid
for the television company.
He also instructed the brokers to sell the shares on the day the takeover
was launched, netting a profit of Pounds 80,000 on the deal. Although the
broker had at first assumed that Lord Archer was buying the shares for
himself when the first order to buy 25,000 shares was placed on January 13,
the novelist gave instructions that they should be registered in the name of
his acquaintance, Mr Broosk Saib.
The following day, Lord Archer bought a second parcel of 25,000 shares for
Mr Saib. However, the address given to the broker for all correspondence
with Mr Saib was that of Lord Archer's London penthouse overlooking the
Thames.
When the shares were sold, the Pounds 80,000 cheque for Mr Saib was sent to
that address.
Lord Archer said last night the DTI must 'be taken to have concluded that
this transaction was not carried out with the benefit of any inside
information'.
The DTI said yesterday it had nothing to add to its statement of July 28,
when it said that it was taking 'no further action against any of the
parties concerned in the investigation'.
New insider trading legislation came into effect as part of the Criminal
Justice Act in April. However, because the Anglia transactions were in
January, the DTI inspectors examined possible offences under the previous
legislation. The legislation was changed after criticism that it was badly
worded.
</TEXT>
