<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 94 / US to expand Cuban refugee camps: Thousands to be detained
at Guantanamo naval base - Havana offers talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES HARDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US announced yesterday it would house tens of thousands of Cuban
refugees indefinitely at its Guantanamo Bay naval base, where the refugee
camps are to be expanded to cope with the continuing exodus.
The Clinton administration, under growing pressure from the tide of refugees
in spite of last week's policy switch to bar them from entering the US, was
yesterday offered talks on the issue without preconditions by Cuba.
Mr Roberto Robaina, Cuba's foreign minister, said on a visit to Chile that
his government was willing to talk to Washington, but would not accept a
dialogue 'in which one side presides and the other listens'. The US said it
would welcome resumption of working-level talks on migration, but had no
plans for broader high-level talks until Cuba demonstrated a commitment to
political and economic reforms.
Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, said camps at Guantanamo Bay in
Cuba, which presently hold 23,000 refugees from both Cuba and Haiti, would
be expanded tohouse up to 40,000 people by the end of next week.
'We are preparing to maintain that (detention) base indefinitely if
necessary until such time as the people can be repatriated to Cuba,' Mr
Perry said.
US officials refused to say explicitly that they would hold refugees until
the Castro regime fell, but said they would be detained until they could be
repatriated to Cuba - which US law currently presently forbids.
The US coastguard rescued 1,159 Cubans by mid-afternoon yesterday after
3,253 were picked up on Tuesday, another record for one day. Mr Perry said
that of the 9,000 refugees picked up in recent weeks, 2,000 were already
held at Guantanamo Bay and the other 7,000 were on their way there.
The administration again warned Cubans not to attempt the dangerous
crossing, with a stern reminder that those picked up at sea and taken to
Guantanamo would never get into the US.
'Do not risk your lives,' said Ms Janet Reno, attorney-general. 'You will
not be processed for admission to the US.'
Ms Reno urged those wanting to leave to pursue legal emigration by taking
advantage of the 28,000 visas reserved for them annually in Cuba.
Mr Perry also said that, contrary to some reports, he had 'no evidence' of
Cubans congregating on the country's border with the US base at Guantanamo.
If Cuba allowed this to happen, the US 'would regard this as being an
unfriendly act (and) take appropriate actions', he said.
Although the administration hopes to see a drop in numbers of refugees over
the next week as its policy change hits home, the State Department is
negotiating to set up third-country safe havens in the region.
Mr Peter Tarnoff, deputy secretary of state, confirmed that the US expects
to conclude arrangements with the Turks and Caicos Islands - a British
dependency - as well as Surinam and Panama.
Mr Tarnoff rejected the idea of discussions with Cuba's leader-ship. Earlier
yesterday, Mr Fernando Remirez de Estenoz Barciela, Cuba's ambassador to the
United Nations, said his country was prepared to discuss the refugee
problem, but only as part of broader negotiations.
Cuban exiles await green light from US, Page 4
</TEXT>
