<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow climbs on bonds and
progress at Deere
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks rallied yesterday on news of a strong quarterly performance by
Deere, the farm equipment manufacturer, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 24.61 higher at 3,775.83, while
the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 2.20 ahead at 464.51.
Activity on the Big Board was brisk, with 307m shares traded by the close.
Advancing issues led declines by nearly a two-to-one margin.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was up 0.51 at 446.28,
and the Nasdaq composite gained 5.69 to 747.97.
After several days of weakness, stocks opened higher and advanced steadily
until the late afternoon. The improvement came as investors suspended
nagging concerns over the impact of higher interest rates on corporate
profitability.
The change in tone was partly explained by a firming trend in bonds, which
had dragged down share prices since the day after last week's move to
tighter credit conditions. Treasuries posted modest gains as the dollar
ended the day slightly stronger against other leading currencies.
The session's most influential development was the release of a surprisingly
robust earnings report by Deere. In addition to revealing impressive gains
in third-quarter revenue and net income, the company said that it was
boosting its North American production schedule in view of an expanding
economy and the improved outlook for US farm incomes.
The announcement triggered fresh enthusiasm for many stocks whose
performances are closely linked to broad economic trends. The rebound by
such cyclical issues suggested investors were hedging their bets on the
direction of the economy in the coming months. At the very least, the
company's results encouraged some bargain-hunting.
Deere was the greatest beneficiary of the mood swing, its share price
jumping 5 per cent or Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 69 1/2 . Agco, a Deere
competitor, gained Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 45 1/4 . Among the Dow
industrials, Caterpillar set the pace with a gain of Dollars 4 3/8 to
Dollars 111 5/8 , while Allied Signal climbed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 35
3/4 .
Elsewhere, Cummins Engine improved Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 40 7/8 and Clark
Equipment was up Dollars 1 7/8 at Dollars 68 1/2 .
In the consumer non-durable sector, Philip Morris was Dollars 1 1/4 better
at Dollars 56 1/2 . Investors were anticipating the company would raise its
dividend or announce a share repurchase program at next week's annual
meeting.
Canada
Toronto stocks closed higher with a solid gain. The TSE-300 composite index
was up 25.26 points, or 0.60 per cent, to 4,211.68.
Losing issues, however, held a slight lead over winners by 378 to 373.
Volume rose to 73.69m shares worth CDollars 979.5m from Monday's 46.26m
valued at CDollars 532.6m.
Mexico
Equities surrendered early gains to show a slight loss on profit-taking and
unconfirmed market rumours of post-electoral trouble in the southern state
of Chiapas.
The IPC index of 37 leading shares closed 3.44 points, or 0.12 per cent,
lower at 2,755.33 after earlier soaring to 2,800.86 in heavy volume trading.
After peeping above the psychological 2,800-point level, the market began
falling back on profit-taking and the rumours accelerated the decline.
Of the 127 issues traded, 80 were still higher and 30 were down with 17
unchanged.
Telmex L shares were down 0.18 percent although its A shares were up 0.18
percent. Telmex ADRs were down  5/8 to 65 7/8 in New York.
Brazil
Mild profit-taking cut stock prices in Sao Paulo market by 1.5 per cent at
the close as the market staged a small correction to a 28 per cent rise in
the first three weeks of August.
The Bovespa index of the 56 most-active shares ended down 818 at 53,040
points. On the Rio bourse, the ISENN fell 1.1 per cent to 20,548 points.
Turnover was 442.3m reais (Dollars 499.2m).
</TEXT>
