<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries show slight gain as dollar
stalls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury bonds were finishing with slight gains yesterday after tracking
the dollar's movements in the foreign exchange markets.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was up  5/32 at
99 15/32 , with the yield slipping to 7.538 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was up  1/16 at 99 27/32 , to yield 6.192 per cent.
For the second day, there was no fresh economic guidance to push prices out
of their tight range. Traders again focused their attention on the dollar,
which recovered some lost ground against other leading currencies in the
early going, only to slip back in the afternoon.
The reaction to the greenback's early improvement was favourable, though
restrained. By midday, securities across the maturity range showed modest
gains in light trading.
Activity picked up in the early afternoon, when strong demand surfaced for a
Treasury auction of Dollars 17.25bn in new two-year notes. Bonds extended
their gains when the issue was awarded with a yield of 6.27 per cent, a
little lower than expected.
But the rally was quickly aborted, partly due to the dollar's inability to
hold its early gains. The market's timidity after the successful two-year
sale did not bode well for today's auction of Dollars 11bn in five-year
securities.
European government bond markets got off to a weak start yesterday as
traders remained wary in the absence of any economic data. But they
recovered in the afternoon due to a technical 'squeeze' which forced dealers
wanting to cover their short positions to chase bond prices higher.
The release today of US durable goods orders data for July and news from
Germany on inflation in August could provide the markets with a fresh
direction, analysts said. However, they said volume was likely to remain
thin until the end of the holiday season. 'There is no fundamental reason
for investors to get involv-ed,' said Mr Sanjay Joshi, chief economist at
Daiwa Europe.
The main casualty of the day was the Italian government bond market, which
fell heavily at the opening on a newspaper report which appeared to suggest
that the government was considering a rise in the withholding tax on
government short-term bills and certificates to 15 per cent from 12.5 per
cent.
On Liffe, September Italian government bond futures lost 1 1/2 points to the
day's low of 97.54 in reaction to the interview with Mr Filippo Berselli,
under-secretary at the finance ministry. But they recovered to trade around
98.33 in late afternoon, down 0.47 point on the day, after the official said
that the government had no plans to raise the tax.
Mr Julian Jessop, international economist at Midland Global Markets, said
that in spite of yesterday's confusion, a rise in the tax was not out of the
question. Indeed, such a move could well be accepted by the market if it was
presented as part of a decent package of measures aimed at tackling the
budget deficit. In any case most overseas investors did not pay the tax, he
said.
News that the Bundespost was issuing DM2.5bn worth of 10-year paper did not
thrill the bund market but prices ended higher on the day due to technical
short-covering. On Liffe, the September bund future stood 0.23 point higher
at 91.46 in late trading, off the day's low of 90.96.
Some dealers were hopeful that better-than-expected inflation data would
provide some relief. A rise in the yearly rate to 3 per cent from 2.9 per
cent had already been discounted by the market so a flat result could well
produce a recovery, they said.
The firmer tone in bunds and a minor rebound in sterling helped UK gilts
stage a late rally although the long end did better than the short end of
the yield curve. On Liffe, the September long gilt future rose by 1/8 point
to 100 7/8 in later trading, off the day's low of 100 5/32.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
