<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Scramble for a slice of the nitty-gritty market: A look at
the hotting up of competition between US long-distance telecoms operators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The obsession with 'superhighways' and high-tech 'convergence' has obscured
the dominant trend in the US telecommunications industry: the massive
intensification of competition between operators vying to provide core
telecoms services.
This week's Dollars 2.5bn (Pounds 1.6bn) purchase of WilTel, a US
long-distance operator, by LDDS, the acquisitive US telecoms group,
underlines that reality. LDDS's ambition is simple: to establish itself as
the fourth force in US long-distance and international telecoms, challenging
AT&amp;T, MCI and Sprint.
LDDS is elbowing its way into a crowded market. Long-distance telecoms in
the US has been fiercely competitive for a decade, since AT&amp;T was forced to
spin off its local networks and the remainder of its business was exposed to
newcomers.
AT&amp;T steadily lost market share until stabilising at about 60 per cent of
long-distance traffic. The main beneficiary was MCI, which rose to about 20
per cent on the back of aggressive discounting and innovative marketing.
Sprint took a 10 per cent stake, while hundreds of smaller resale operators
 -WilTel being one of the largest - established themselves by discounting.
LDDS has forged a profitable business in the past 10 years reselling leased
telecoms lines at a discount to small and medium-sized business customers.
Last year the Mississippi-based group merged with Metromedia Communications,
the long-distance telephone and entertainment concern owned by Mr John
Kluge, a billionaire businessman with ambitions to take on the 'big three'
long-distance operators.
Earlier this year, LDDS's first offer for WilTel was rejected by Williams
Companies, the Oklahoma-based owner. LDDS paid Dollars 895m for IDB
Communications, an international satellite phone carrier before returning
for WilTel with a Dollars 2.5bn offer.
With WilTel's 11,000-mile advanced fibre-optic communications network, LDDS
becomes a fully fledged phone carrier. As an owner instead of a lessee of
telecoms lines, it hopes to reduce its costs and offer lower prices and a
broader range of services. It will target larger corporate customers of the
kind traditionally served by the Big Three.
What are its prospects?
LDDS believes it has snatched a head-start on other operators angling to
compete in long-distance services, notably the seven 'Baby Bell' regional
companies which hope to enter the market on the back of regulatory changes
expected to be enacted by Congress this year.
It is debatable, however, how much of a market opportunity exists. AT&amp;T and
its rivals will not yield business without a fight. Price differentials are
already low: according to analysts, a 3 to 8 per cent margin separates the
operators.
Moreover, new services increasingly depend upon sophisticated network
software, and the larger operators are to the fore in its development. AT&amp;T
estimates that within five years half its revenue from business customers
could come from services other than telephone calls.
Nonetheless, LDDS starts with about 4 per cent of a Dollars 65bn market
which is expanding rapidly. All customers are becoming used to switching
operators, and many businesses are employing multiple long-distance
providers.
Much depends on whether Congress passes the current telecommunications bill,
which would further open up the industry. Mr Stuart Conrad, analyst at CJ
Lawrence Deutsche Bank Securities, says charges imposed by local operators
are declining at an annual rate of 3-4 per cent and could fall by as much as
20 per cent within three years, if Congress permits greater local
competition.
If LDDS establishes a profitable niche, it might itself become a takeover
target, particularly for the Baby Bells as they look for a short-cut into
the long-distance business. Alternatively, a data information company might
take a look: last week the company's shares were buoyed by rumours that
Electronic Data Systems, the computer services company owned by General
Motors, was considering merging with LDDS, although Mr Bernard Ebbers,
LDDS's chief executive, denies that talks took place.
LDDS is also developing an international strategy. Mr Ebbers says 'there may
be an opportunity' in tying up with an overseas operator. Cable &amp; Wireless,
the UK telecoms group, is keen to strengthen its position in the US market,
where it has a small long-distance business.
Mr Ebbers says his priority is to weld together the existing business.
However, in today's telecoms industry, there is no such thing as a breathing
space.
Lex, Page 14; Delta joint venture, Page 17; Video conference picture begins
to clear, Page 18
</TEXT>
