<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Thorn stalls on demerger: Music and rentals group sees 18%
fall in first-quarter profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Colin Southgate, Thorn EMI's chairman, yesterday firmly ruled out an
early demerger of the music and rentals group and said the proposal was now
'on the back-burner'.
Sir Colin, speaking as Thorn unveiled an 18 per cent fall in first-quarter
pre-tax profits reflecting exceptional charges, said: 'I don't think we will
look at demerger again for three years.' There was 'no indication of any
terrific upside value' in a demerger of the group's core music and retail
divisions and he noted that the costs would be huge.
Thorn's shares, which have rallied recently on revived speculation of a
demerger, closed down 9p at 1054p.
The group's results for the three months to June 30 - the first time Thorn
has reported the first quarter - showed a strong performance by its main
businesses, EMI Music, Thorn Group and HMV, together with an improvement in
its other businesses.
However, pre-tax profits fell to Pounds 33.1m from Pounds 40.4m after a net
exceptional charge of Pounds 13.1m, mainly on the disposal of Thorn
Security, which was partly offset by a decline in finance charges
to Pounds 6.2m (Pounds 12.5m).
Turnover from continuing operations increased to Pounds 928.8m (Pounds
870.8m) with discontinued operations contributing a further Pounds 2.3m
(Pounds 147.9m). The group sold Thorn Lighting and its stake in Thames
Television.
Profits from continuing operations rose 24.7 per cent to Pounds 52.5m
(Pounds 42.1m).
Sales at EMI Music rose 16.6 per cent to Pounds 404.9m and profits grew by
14.6 per cent to Pounds 33m helped by the success of Canto Gregoriano and
Pink Floyd's latest album.
Thorn Group, the renamed rental business, posted a 9.8 per cent increase in
operating profit to Pounds 25.8m on revenues which rose 6.2 per cent to
Pounds 374.1m, underpinned by improvement in both UK and continental
European businesses.
Sales at HMV increased 12.4 per cent to Pounds 87.8m with its seasonal loss
falling 24.4 per cent to Pounds 3.4m. Store sales continued to grow on a
like-for-like basis and the group opened a further six shops to bring its
total to 188 stores worldwide.
Net borrowings at the end of June stood at Pounds 471.5m representing
gearing of 38.3 per cent.
Earnings per share fell to 3.1p (6.4p) on a fully diluted basis.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
