<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Lilley takes shine off City bonuses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
City firms accustomed to paying high-flying dealers with diamonds or cases
of Chateau Lafite to avoid National Insurance contributions will now have to
search for even more imaginative loopholes in the law.
From midnight last night, gemstones and a range of alcoholic drinks will be
treated as payments of earnings, liable for National Insurance
contributions, Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, announced
yesterday.
This could include favourites such as Chateau Lafite 1990 retailing at about
Pounds 700 a case or, perhaps, Chateau Pichon la Lande, which sells for
Pounds 400 a case, according to one wine broker who has supplied wine for
city bonuses.
The move, expected to save the exchequer about Pounds 50m a year, is the
latest attempt to close loopholes which have enabled mostly large City firms
to avoid paying the 10.2 per cent employers' contributions on bonus
payments.
It follows action by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, in the last Budget
to prevent gold bars and other tradeable commodities being used to avoid
contributions, saving an estimated Pounds 70m a year. The government has
previously acted to prevent gilts and shares in other companies being paid
to avoid tax.
Mr Lilley said yesterday: 'Companies and their accountant advisers who
devise ways of paying earnings which avoid their liability for National
Insurance contributions will find it increasingly unattractive to produce
and operate such schemes.
'These regulations are clear evidence of the government's intention to act
speedily to close National Insurance loopholes.'
Officials are thought to have uncovered about 50 schemes involving diamonds
or fine wines. These escaped the budget measures because they were not
traded on a recognised exchange.
The Royal Bank of Canada has assisted customers making diamond-backed
payments by enabling gems to be bought and sold without leaving Switzerland,
thus avoiding the payment of value added tax.
It said yesterday: 'The operation, which was only a very small part of our
business will no longer apply.'
Accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand, which advises clients on how to limit tax
bills, said: 'These schemes were attractive mainly to City firms paying
large bonuses to individual staff, rather than the run-of-mill bonus
schemes.'
</TEXT>
