<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / The Lex Column: NFC loses driver
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
NFC's statement on the resignation of chief executive Mr Peter Sherlock left
everything to the imagination. The company provided no explanation at all,
not even that traditional fig leaf, 'after a clash of management styles'. To
be fair to NFC, Bass was no more illuminating when Mr Sherlock left its
employ in October 1992. Whatever the reasons, shareholders of both companies
may begrudge paying Mr Sherlock over Pounds 1m in compensation for loss of
office in under two years.
The bigger worry for NFC shareholders is that there is more to Mr Sherlock's
departure than personalities. While his business school jargon may not have
been to every investment institution's taste, his arrival was welcomed by
those keen to see NFC's inbred culture opened up. They will not be reassured
that the board appears to have sided with Mr Robbie Burns, a life-long NFC
man who was beaten to the top job by Mr Sherlock and has now withdrawn his
own resignation. Although the company stresses that there has been no change
in strategic direction, the suspicion remains that Mr Sherlock wanted to
pursue it more quickly than Mr Burns.
The management question would matter less if Mr Sherlock's bullish comments
about trading prospects had proved accurate. Third quarter figures suggest
operating profit growth remains very sluggish. NFC may be right to blame
both European recession and American overheating for its problems. But the
new chief executive will need to do more to convince investors it can
capitalise on the undoubted opportunities.
</TEXT>
