FT  24 AUG 94 / Observer: Anchors away
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Rear-admiral Allison Madueke - just sacked as chief of staff of the Nigerian
navy - will no doubt look back with nostalgia on his nine months in the job.
An Ibo who once fought on the rebel side in the Biafran war, he probably
relished his staff mansion in Lagos's exclusive Ikoyi suburb.
Not that running Nigeria's navy is particularly demanding, aside from
receiving visiting warships from Brazil. It might be the largest navy in
west Africa but has never had to fire a shot in anger. Of the two frigates
moored in Lagos, the Obuma is not in operation - except for an annual spin
round the harbour - while the Iradu has been undergoing repairs for two
years.
Perhaps Madueke will get a consolation prize. Local press reports suggest
the number two in the regime, General Oladipo Diya, may be the next victim
of General Abacha's reshuffle - with Madueke tipped for the job. Lucky him.
