<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Post office closure claims rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Federation of Sub-Postmasters yesterday denied that government
plans to sell 51 per cent of the Royal Mail and Parcelforce to the private
sector would lead inevitably to the closure of many post offices.
Mr Colin Baker, the federation's general secretary, said that there was 'no
evidence whatsoever' that the sale would result in widespread closures.
His statement came as the Labour party released the results of a survey of
500 of the country's 19,000 local postmasters and postmistresses. Mr Robin
Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said the people who ran post
office branches believed by a majority of five to one that the government
would be wrong to break up the organisation.
By a majority of three to one they thought privatisation would force more
small post offices to close, he said.
Mr Baker said the federation was concerned about 'blatant scaremongering
stories of massive sub-office closures' and felt it vital that such rumours
should be scotched.
But he acknowledged that the organisation, which represents Britain's
sub-postmasters and postmistresses, had concerns about separating the parts
of the system.
He said there were still 'many questions' to be answered arising from this
year's government green paper, relating particularly to automation and the
future size of the post office network.
Mr Cook said that post office users did not want to see the organisation
sold off as a private business.
Referring to a tour he had made recently of British post offices, he said he
had not met such universal hostility to a government plan since the poll
tax.
In an attempt to engender misgivings about the government's proposals among
Conservative MPs nursing shaky majorities, he said opposition was 'as strong
in Tory Kent as in Labour Tyneside'.
Mr John Roberts, chairman of Post Office Counters, said that the post
offices network was not at risk, adding that the Post Office warmly welcomed
the government's pledge that the link between a privatised Royal Mail and
post offices would be guaranteed in law.
</TEXT>
