FT  24 AUG 94 / BT plans 'smart' cards for callboxes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications yesterday announced that it was going ahead with
a system of phonecards and payphones based on 'smart card' integrated
microchip technology.
BT said the cards would improve the reliability of payphones and could lead
to the introduction of multi-purpose cards designed for a range of
functions, such as paying for goods in shops.
BT plans to introduce the payphones from next year.
Three companies, including GPT, the UK-based joint venture between GEC and
Siemens, will provide payphones able to accept smart phonecards. Two
companies, Gemplus and GPT, will produce the phonecards.
The smart phonecard will be a prepaid card similar to existing phonecards
and will be used in a similar way.
BT said the new payphones would be conventional in appearance and offer a
cash-and-card or card-only payment option.
