<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / British Coal aims to cut more jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Coal yesterday started negotiations for a final reduction of staff
before privatisation. The move is expected to lead to more than 2,000 job
losses by the end of the year.
In talks with three unions the corporation was unable to state exactly how
many jobs would go but said the cuts would be broadly limited to management
and clerical staff at national, regional and group headquarters.
Of British Coal's 14,000 industrial employees and staff, about 10,000 are
miners with the rest either managers or white-collar workers. Most of those
not working in pits are unlikely to be needed by the corporation's
successors.
The government has asked bidders for the five core mining regions to present
their tenders by September 14 and is expected to select a preferred
candidate for each soon after. It wants to complete the sale of all five,
plus any closed mines that the private sector wants to re-open, on December
24.
Mr Kevan Hunt, British Coal employee-relations director, told the unions
that the government's sale of the core mining activities was progressing on
schedule. In addition, the corporation's sale of non-core businesses was
attracting considerable interest. Many of British Coal's 4,000 non-miner
employees are employed in these businesses.
Mr Hunt called on miners who had not yet accepted flexible working packages
to 'focus their attention' during the next few days. They have been given a
deadline of August 31 to decide.
The packages provide miners with one-off payments of Pounds 6,000 and allow
for redundancy packages of up to Pounds 27,000 if they lose their jobs
before March 1998. They must also, however, agree to work rosters which can
include shifts of up to 12 hours and weekend work.
</TEXT>
