<DATE>940824
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Stream of cuts erodes help for disabled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last year Remploy drew Pounds 13m from Ministry of Defence contracts as a
result of the priority suppliers scheme. The orders were to provide military
clothing and chemical protection suits
But earlier this month the government decided to scrap the scheme to comply
with a strict interpretation of a European directive. Mr Tony Withey, chief
executive of Remploy, said: 'We knew that the withdrawal of the scheme would
make life difficult for us.'
It is the company's textile division, which gets 65 per cent of its business
from the MoD, that could be hardest hit.
Remploy was set up in 1946 to provide work for the war-wounded and has
maintained a commitment to employing a large percentage of disabled workers.
The company employs 8,736 disabled workers - about 99 per cent of its
shopfloor employees - in 95 factories across Britain, providing
manufacturing services in furniture, packaging, textiles, healthcare,
bookbinding and printing.
In the past Remploy has been able to rely on a steady stream of work from
government departments. But the loss of the priority supplier scheme is only
one of a number of government cuts that have affected its business.
Last year the government lowered a subsidy intended to cover the costs of
employing disabled workers, although Mr Michael Portillo, the employment
secretary, has said this subsidy should help Remploy maintain a competitive
edge after the disappearance of the priority scheme.
The company is also suffering from the government's competitive tendering
policy. Last year it lost about Pounds 5m in government contracts with the
Employment Service and the National Health Service.
Mr Withey said that the shift from centralised buying gave his workforce
unique problems. When government contracts were offered centrally, workers
could be taught skills particular to one large bid. But many of the
company's severely disabled workers were unable to cope with the wide range
of product specifications in a decentralised market.
The company has 10,400 employees. Although its disabled staff represent
about 85 per cent of its workforce, they command only about 75 per cent of
Remploy's payroll costs.
Remploy is in dispute with its unions over a recent pay offer, which has
prompted the GMB general union, the largest of the company's six-union
consortium, to hold a strike ballot.
The company is offering a 2.5 per cent pay rise and the only condition is
that the unions co-operate with management on absence monitoring.
</TEXT>
