<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Struggle over crime bill in Senate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton's crime bill ran into another brick wall yesterday,
when the administration and the Democratic leadership in the Senate fell
short in their efforts to muster enough votes to overcome a procedural
obstacle raised by the opposition Republicans.
Senator Joseph Biden, the crime bill's manager in the Senate, conceded in a
long and bitter speech yesterday evening that he was at least one vote short
of the 60 he would need to waive a budgetary point of order raised against
the bill.
Although debate will continue today while efforts continue behind the scenes
to drum up more support, the failure to bring the bill to a vote yesterday
was another devastating blow to Mr Clinton.
Without the waiver, Mr Biden said, the crime bill would die until a new
Congress could start afresh next year.
A waiver is required because the bill sets up a trust fund, to be filled
with money saved from cutting the federal government workforce, to pay for
its law enforcement measures. The trust fund was not voted on by the budget
committee, and so technically violates the Congressional Budget Act.
If the point of order is not set aside, the legislation would once again be
opened up for amendment. That would mean that sending it back once again to
the House of Representatives, which only passed it on Sunday after the
Democrats had made a series of concessions to overcome a similar procedural
obstacle.
When the crime bill passed the Senate for the first time late last year, the
Republicans voted overwhelmingly for it, and agreed to waive the budgetary
point of order.
Scenting blood from a weakened president, the Republicans moved in for the
kill to raise the point of order this time around. Senator Pete Domenici of
New Mexico claimed yesterday that the bill had been so altered in the
conference to reconcile it with the House version that the waiver he and his
colleagues had earlier supported was no longer justified.
</TEXT>
