<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / World Trade News: Otis in second Vietnam deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Otis Elevator, the world's largest lift producer, has signed its second
joint venture agreement in Vietnam since President Bill Clinton lifted the
US economic embargo against the country in February.
The Connecticut-based lift and escalator maker, part of United Technologies,
is joining forces with Ho Chi Minh City's Construction and Elevator Company
(CEC) to sell, install, maintain and modernise lifts and escalators in the
southern part of Vietnam.
Otis announced a similar deal in May with the Hanoi-based Lilama
construction concern to cover the north of the country. The US lift company
now has a majority stake in both of these ventures, in which it has invested
a total of Dollars 4.5m.
Otis Elevators has moved quickly since the lifting of the embargo, because
it had been worried that its European and other rivals might move into the
promising Vietnamese market.
Otis claims to be the first international liftmaker to return to Vietnam. In
1929 it had installed one of the country's oldest lifts at the presidential
palace in Hanoi, and formal operations began in 1950, only to cease in 1975
with the US withdrawal.
Otis believes that, with more than 15m of Vietnam's 72m population living in
eight big cities, there is substantial potential for new lift sales and
service. Plans to redress the shortage of offices, hotels and industrial
buildings should also promote demand.
The latest joint venture, to be known as Otis Saigon Elevator,
re-establishes a relationship with CEC, which under the name Engineco was
the Otis agent in Vietnam from 1968 to 1975. It will initially employ about
50 people rising to an expected 250 within five years.
Lifts and escalators will be supplied from Otis' new manufacturing plant on
Penang island in Malaysia.
</TEXT>
