<DATE>940824
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Workforce cuts now less likely: Adjustment to high yen
complete
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most Japanese companies believe they have made the adjustments to their
workforces necessary to cope with the high yen, according to a survey
released by the labour ministry yesterday.
Of about 1,000 employers it polled in mid-July, only 4 per cent said they
had taken steps to shed jobs since the currency began its renewed climb in
June. A further 6 per cent were planning such measures.
A previous survey conducted last August, when the yen first touched the Y100
level against the US dollar, showed that 10 per cent of companies had taken
recent action and a further 10 per cent intended to do so if the exchange
rate stayed at current levels.
The yen closed in Tokyo yesterday at Y98.13 to the dollar, held back by Bank
of Japan intervention after strong overnight buying in New York pushed it as
high as Y97.85.
Mr Ryutaro Hashimoto, international trade and industry minister, told a
press conference he was worried that the effect of the strong currency on
export performance would hinder a nascent economic recovery.
And Mr Toshio Morikawa, chairman of the Federation of Bankers Associations
of Japan, while saying the country was certainly headed for an upturn,
cautioned the level of the yen would mean revival was slow.
If the currency rose further, 30 per cent of the companies surveyed by the
labour ministry said they would have to take action. Half the sample had
previously carried out some sort of employment adjustment amid the country's
three-year economic downturn.
As the Japanese lifetime employment system inhibits compulsory redundancies,
measures commonly include transferring workers to affiliates and offering
early retirement incentives. But the number of new programmes of this type
reported is falling.
The government's Economic Planning Agency said yesterday the economy was on
the dividing line between recession and recovery, according to its diffusion
index for June. The coincident index, reflecting prevailing conditions,
stood at 50 per cent. It had been above that level for the past three
months, achieving its most optimistic recent scores of 60 per cent in April
and May, but the agency said the fall was milder than expected.
The leading index, which projects conditions three to six months ahead,
stood at 54.5 per cent, compared with 58.3 per cent in May. It was the sixth
successive reading above the boom-or-bust level. The lagging index rose to
42.9 per cent, below the halfway mark for the ninth month in a row but up
from 14.3 per cent in May.
The EPA spoke of a heightened possibility the economy was moving into
recovery, and dropped a previous description of conditions as sluggish. But
it warned the July index might show no progress, because of weak industrial
output.
</TEXT>
