<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 94 / Benetton grand prix team changes gear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Benetton Formula, the leading grand prix racing team this year, is ending
its eight-year partnership with Ford, its engine supplier, in favour of
Renault. The French carmaker announced yesterday it had reached agreement to
supply Formula One engines to the Benetton team for the next three years
starting in 1995.
The deal comes only two weeks after the British Williams racing team renewed
its contract with Renault to supply engines for three more years.
The Renault coup of securing contracts with two of the leading F1 teams is a
considerable blow to Ford and to Cosworth Engineering, a subsidiary of
Vickers, which builds the engines for Ford.
The Benetton team, with its German driver Michael Schumacher, is currently
leading the 1994 Formula One world championship having won seven of the
season's first 10 races.
Despite its success with the Ford Zetec-R V8 engine built by Cosworth,
Benetton has decided that its fortunes next year will be enhanced by using
the same Renault engines as the Williams team, its arch rival.
Mr Flavio Briatore, managing director of Benetton Formula, said he was
confident that the new partnership with Renault would 'enhance the
performance of both parties.'
Renault said that the deals with Benetton and the Williams racing team
underlined its resolve to maintain a long-term presence in Formula One. 'The
objective is to win grand prix and to be champion of the world,' said Mr
Patrick Faure, director of Renault Sport. 'Our presence in Formula One is
only justified by winning.'
Renault said nothing had been hidden from the Williams team. 'At the
beginning they were not very enthusiastic. But they understood our
arguments,' the company said. Benetton and Williams would be supplied with
identical engines in 1995.
The attraction for Renault is to be teamed with Michael Schumacher, who has
emerged as the leading Formula One driver this season, ousting Williams from
the head of the championship.
Ford, which mounts one of the biggest motor sports programmes of any of the
world's carmakers, sought last night to put a brave face on the loss of the
Benetton contract.
Mr Peter Gillitzer, director of Ford Motorsport strategy in Europe, said the
company was 'presently reviewing' its plans. 'The success of the Ford
Zetec-R engine is unquestioned and it still has substantial development
potential. It is a very competitive unit. We are currently talking to a
number of people about our future strategy.'
Ford Cosworth engines are being used by five teams in this year's
championship, including Minardi, Arrows Footwork, Simtek and Larrousse, but
the Benetton team is its key contract.
</TEXT>
