<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / International Company News: CME seeks strength through
harmonisation - The exchange plans to merge its financial and agricultural
sectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Chicago Mercantile Exchange is close to making a fundamental shift in
governance that for the first time would give its member banks and other
financial traders a free hand in guiding its future.
The realignment would put the exchange, which already doubles its business
very five years, in an even stronger position to compete internationally and
allow it to venture into new product areas.
The CME is home to the world's largest futures contract, eurodollar or
short-term dollar interest rate futures, and boasts the most expensive
memberships of any exchange. Seat values are approaching Dollars 1m, with
the most aggressive bidders international banks which find the CME plays an
essential role in their interest rate risk management and derivatives
strategies.
In spite of its high profile in global financial markets, the CME's roots
are in agricultural products, and until recently a small handful of pork
belly and live cattle traders had final say on important items on the
exchange's agenda. Having a few 'cowboys' hold sway over a group of
international banks has long been viewed as inappropriate - particularly
when sensitive issues of financial regulation are being considered - but
because the agricultural block holds most of the voting power, there seemed
little prospect for change.
Now, long-time chairman Jack Sandner, is manoeuvring a quiet revolution. He
hopes to merge the exchange's robust financial division with its obscure but
politically powerful agricultural sector as early as October.
'It's time to harmonise the agenda of the exchange,' he says. 'We have two
different interest groups, and on some issues the division has the potential
to tear us apart. To avoid parochial issues and arguments, we have to unify.
We're really here to facilitate trade, and that is what we need to focus
on.'
Five years ago such a statement could have cost Mr. Sandner his chair.
However, with CME seat values double what they were last year, Mr Sandner is
enjoying unprecedented popularity at the exchange, and has the backing of
important membership blocks.
The US futures industry also appears to be ready for the shift, with several
executives noting that this summer's merger of New York's two largest
exchanges set a valuable precedent for the Chicago initiative. As with the
New York merger, the CME is prepared to dip into its treasury to compensate
its agricultural members for their loss of political clout and the premium
their memberships have commanded.
Although the consolidation is being played in Chicago as a purely internal
issue, it has serious implications for the exchange's future. With its
Reuters-owned after-hours trading system, Globex, eclipsed by successful
systems elsewhere, the exchange faces difficult decisions about investing in
other ex-pit trading technology.
A unified membership that could share equally from returns on such
investments would give the exchange a freer hand at strategic planning.
Similarly, Mr Sandner's initiative to make the exchange a for-profit entity
would also be forwarded by a self-interested membership.
The consolidation might also breathe new life into the CME's languishing
agricultural futures, and into new contracts that have difficulty attracting
traders.
One by-product of the CME's soaring seat prices is that the price of entry
into the exchange is now so high that few traders can afford to linger in
inactive pits.
The reorganisation is expected to open these pits to more of the exchange's
existing membership, and may also produce a new, inexpensive 'mini-seat'
that could be used exclusively for trading small contracts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
