<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / International Company News: Banesto sees 'positive' result
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Banco Espanol de Credito (Banesto) yesterday attempted to reassure
shareholders it was on a stable footing, eight months after a summary
intervention by the Bank of Spain.
Mr Alfredo Saenz, chairman of the group controlled by Banco Santander, said
it was already 'a normalised bank' and forecast that the second half would
produce 'more positive' results after a first-half loss of Pta21.8bn
(Dollars 168m).
He said the bank had engaged US lawyers to contest a suit filed this month
in New York by Carlisle Ventures, a unit of Northwestern Mutual Life
Insurance. Carlisle claims it was misled when it subscribed to a Banesto
capital increase in 1993 and is seeking repayment of Dollars 27.5m. The
institutional tranche of the Pta94bn rights issue was priced at Pta1,900 a
share, compared with yesterday's closing price of Pta1,075.
The Banesto shareholders' meeting yesterday approved a motion of censure
against the previous management, which was removed by the Bank of Spain in
December.
Consolidated 1993 accounts published yesterday showed losses of Pta584.6bn,
with total non-performing assets for the group increasing to Pta898.1bn from
Pta257.4bn in 1992. Mr Saenz said the bank had made 'encouraging progress'
in recovering non-performing loans. Revised 1993 losses for the parent bank
were Pta577.9bn, compared with a pre-tax profit of Pta23.8bn last time.
Mr Saenz said the bank had decided to cancel its contract with accountants
Price Waterhouse and entrust its future audits to Arthur Andersen.
The meeting marked the completion of a rescue plan involving a Pta180bn
capital injection, aid of Pta285bn to mop up non-performing assets, and a
Pta315bn interest-free loan from Spain's Deposit Guarantee Fund.
</TEXT>
