</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Celsius, the Swedish defence group privatised last year, yesterday announced
pre-tax profits of SKr379m (Dollars 48.6m) for the first six months, up 20
per cent from SKr315m a year ago.
The group attributed the improvement to structural change and greater
efficiency and to a SKr600m increase in sales to SKr6.7bn.
However, its performance had been dragged down by turbulence in the bond
markets, which sharply lowered returns from last year's very high levels and
cut financial income to SKr33m from SKr205m, the group said.
The fall meant the group did not feel the full benefits of a strong advance
in operating income to SKr346m from SKr110m. Orders rose SKr800m to
SKr5.8bn, including a SKr270m order to build four minehunters for the
Swedish navy.
The group forecasts a full-year profit of SKr800m, compared with SKr721m
last year. It anticipates continued growth in operating income as well as
higher return on its financial investments.
