<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / Pentagon seeks sweeping cuts in weapons spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Pentagon has ordered a sweeping review of almost all its main weapons
programmes in an effort to squeeze defence spending over the next five years
into a shrinking budget.
The military services have been told to prepare to cancel, delay or arrange
substitutes for all their most costly equipment plans, including the Air
Force's F-22 fighter, the Army's Comanche helicopter, the Navy's Aegis
destroyer and the Marines' V-22 Osprey tilt-rotor aircraft.
Mr William Perry, the defence secretary, said the services had requested
more money for the 1996 fiscal year than the administration's budget would
allow.
He had therefore 'given them some guidance on where to cut' to ensure that
service chiefs did not try to preserve pet weapon systems by scrimping on
operations and training budgets, which he views as essential if US forces
are to maintain full readiness.
'This doesn't mean that they'll be cut. It's just to say that these are not
sacred cows,' Mr Perry said yesterday.
In a memorandum to service chiefs, Mr John Deutch, Mr Perry's deputy,
targeted 10 key weapons programmes for cancellation or delay.
Mr Deutch told the Air Force to develop a plan for delaying acquisition of
the F-22 fighter, built by Lockheed and Boeing.
The Air Force currently plans to acquire over 48 F-22s a year, starting in
1998, at a cost of Dollars 71bn.( Pounds 45.8bn).
The F-22 is the Air Force's most cherished project, and delaying its
acquisition would complicate plans for replacing the F-16 strike aircraft in
the next century.
But Army officials have already started sniping at the F-22, which they say
is designed to give a degree of air superiority that will never be needed
against the third-world enemies the US is now likely to face, and has only
limited ground attack capability.
The Army, in turn, faces the prospect of cancelling its only two major
programmes: the Comanche helicopter and the Advanced Field Artillery System.
The Navy has been asked for plans to slow its shipbuilding programme to an
average of either 2.5 or 2 destroyers a year, with additional delays for its
new attack submarine.
Mr Deutch also asked the Marines to submit the most promising helicopter
alternative to the controversial Osprey, which takes off like a helicopter
but then swings its rotors down to fly like a propeller-driven aircraft. Top
Pentagon officials have tried for years to kill off the expensive and still
experimental aircraft.
Senior members of Congress and government auditors have been warning for
some time that the armed services have failed to scale back their
procurement plans enough to fit within today's budget limits.
But cancelling some of the Pentagon's highest profile weapons systems is
sure to attract criticism from opponents who have attacked the Clinton
administration for cutting defence spending too much.
</TEXT>
<XX>
